inated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to southern China (Guangxi, Guangdong, Yunnan provinces), cultivated since 2700 BCE", "traits": "Evergreen tree 10-15m tall (coppiced to 2-3m), greyish bark, hard elongated leaves 10-15cm long, reddish when young, yellow flowers", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Moderate to high yield, sweeter flavor than Indonesian cassia, 1-2% volatile oil with high cinnamaldehyde (75-90%)", "growing_notes": "One of the 50 fundamental herbs in Traditional Chinese Medicine. Less expensive than Ceylon cinnamon. Available from Asian plant nurseries in Brisbane. Used extensively in curry recipes and Chinese five-spice.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 7}, {"name": "Indonesian Cinnamon (Cinnamomum burmannii) - Korintje", "slug": "indonesian-cinnamon-cinnamomum-burmannii-korintje", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to Indonesia (Sumatra, Java), especially Kerinci region of West Sumatra, cultivated since 1825", "traits": "Small evergreen tree 7m tall, glossy green oval leaves 10cm × 3-4cm, smooth angular branches, red new stems (identifying characteristic), yellow flowers, dark drupe fruits", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "High productivity, most economical cassia type, accounts for 85% of world cassia production", "growing_notes": "Standard cinnamon in US supermarkets. Sweetest, mildest cassia - ideal for baking. Most Americans recognize this flavor from childhood. Available through specialty importers in Brisbane. Jerinci region of Sumatra produces finest quality.", "availability": "", "sort_order": 8}, {"name": "Vietnamese Cinnamon (Cinnamomum loureiroi) - Saigon", "slug": "vietnamese-cinnamon-cinnamomum-loureiroi-saigon", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "Native to Vietnam (Yên Bái, Thanh Hóa, Quảng Nam provinces), named after botanist João de Loureiro", "traits": "Evergreen tree similar to cassia, grows in 